              <div class="col-sm-4">
                <h2>The Problem</h2>

                <p>Three years after Kickstarter launched, we backed our first project: the Double Fine Adventure. At the time, this was the largest project that had ever been on the site. Since then, we've only backed a couple of other projects. Kickstarter is a concept we believe in, and we love directly supporting quality content made by independent creators. Why aren't we using it more?</p>

                <p>Part of the reason is because we only hear about promising Kickstarter projects through some other source that will sometimes refer us to something on the site. We wanted a better way to find projects, so we built Kickammender.
                </p>

              </div>

              <div class="col-sm-4">
                <h2>Our Solution</h2>
                <p></p>
                <p>Kickammender is a demonstration of a better way to find projects on Kickstarter. The heart of our process is the <em>k</em>-means clustering algorithm. We've built that into a dynamic web application using Ruby on Rails. Our application delivers unique recommendations to a user based on their Facebook likes. Additionally, we've built a simple user feedback system and user profile that allows users to tailor our recommendations, save projects they're interested in, and follow Kickstarter users that they like.</p>

                <p>Thanks for taking a look at Kickammender. We hope you find it useful. Read on for a detailed explanation of our methodology, or get in touch with us via Twitter: @jnoconor, @mpolycar. </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
